# UI Quality — Accessibility, Interactivity & Contrast

Every UI element MUST meet GitHub-level quality. These checks are NON-NEGOTIABLE.

## Cursor — Interactive Affordance

Every clickable element MUST show `cursor: pointer`. Every disabled element MUST show `cursor: not-allowed`.

```scss
// REQUIRED on ALL interactive elements
.interactive {
  @apply cursor-pointer;
}

.interactive:disabled {
  @apply cursor-not-allowed;
}
```

### Rules

- `<Button>`, `<IconButton>`, `<Link>` from Primer handle cursor automatically
- When overriding Primer styles with doubled selectors (`.myButton.myButton`), ALWAYS include `cursor-pointer`
- NEVER add `cursor: pointer` to non-interactive elements — it misleads users
- Keyboard focus MUST be visible on all interactive elements (Primer handles this by default)

## Contrast — WCAG AA Minimum

All text MUST meet WCAG AA contrast ratios against its background.

| Requirement | Ratio |
|---|---|
| Normal text (< 18px) | 4.5:1 |
| Large text (≥ 18px bold or ≥ 24px) | 3:1 |
| UI components and borders | 3:1 |

### Token pairing rules

| Background | Allowed text | Forbidden text |
|---|---|---|
| `canvas.default` | `fg.default`, `fg.muted` | `fg.onEmphasis` |
| `canvas.subtle` | `fg.default`, `fg.muted` | `fg.onEmphasis` |
| `accent.emphasis` | `fg.onEmphasis` only | `fg.default`, `fg.muted` |
| `neutral.emphasisPlus` | `fg.onEmphasis` only | `fg.default`, `fg.muted` |

- NEVER pair muted background with muted foreground
- NEVER leave text without an explicit color on dark surfaces

## Primer Primitives CSS — REQUIRED Import

Every web app MUST import the Primer primitives theme CSS in `global.css` to ensure ALL Primer components (inputs, buttons, selects, etc.) render correctly in the active theme.

```css
/* global.css — BEFORE tailwind imports */
@import '@primer/primitives/dist/css/functional/themes/dark.css';
@import '@primer/primitives/dist/css/functional/themes/light.css';
@import 'tailwindcss/theme';
@import 'tailwindcss/utilities';
```

Without this import, Primer components fall back to default styling — inputs lose contrast, buttons lose their colors, and form controls become invisible on dark backgrounds.

## Interactive Elements — Semantic HTML

- Use `<button>` (or Primer `<Button>`) for actions
- Use `<a>` (or Primer `<Link>`) for navigation
- NEVER nest interactive elements (`<a>` inside `<button>` or vice versa)
- For link + button combos, use TanStack Router `<Link>` wrapping a styled `<div>`, NOT `<Link>` wrapping `<Button>`

## Disabled States

- Disabled elements MUST have reduced opacity (`opacity-50` or similar)
- Disabled buttons: `cursor: not-allowed` + visual dimming
- NEVER hide disabled elements — show them dimmed so users understand the option exists

## Focus States

- NEVER remove or override Primer's built-in focus rings
- Custom interactive elements MUST have a visible focus indicator
- Focus order MUST follow visual reading order

## Dark Surface Text

When rendering on any dark surface (rail, sidebar, dark cards):
- ALL text MUST have an explicit color set (never rely on inherited/default colors)
- Use `--primer-fg-on-emphasis` for text on `neutral-emphasis-plus` backgrounds
- Use `--primer-fg-default` for text on `canvas-default` / `canvas-subtle` backgrounds in dark mode

## Loading & Transition States

- Loading buttons: disable + show `<Spinner>` or use Primer's loading patterns
- State transitions: use CSS transitions (`transition-all duration-200 ease-in-out`)
- NEVER flash between states without visual transition

## FORBIDDEN — filter: brightness()

NEVER use `filter: brightness()` for color adjustments. It cascades to ALL child elements, breaking nested Primer components (buttons become invisible, inputs lose contrast, icons change color unintentionally).

```scss
// FORBIDDEN
.rail { filter: brightness(0.75); }

// REQUIRED — use Primer canvas layering
.rail { background-color: var(--primer-canvas-inset); }
.sidebar { background-color: var(--primer-canvas-subtle); }
.content { background-color: var(--primer-canvas-default); }
```

## CSS Specificity — Doubled Selectors

When overriding Primer component styles with doubled selectors (`.foo.foo`), the SAME doubled pattern MUST be used in ALL contexts including media queries. A single selector in a media query CANNOT override a doubled selector.

```scss
// BAD — single selector in media query loses specificity
.backdrop.backdrop { @apply block; }
@include md { .backdrop { @apply hidden; } }

// GOOD — matching specificity
.backdrop.backdrop { @apply block; }
@include md { .backdrop.backdrop { @apply hidden; } }
```

## Module Decomposition — Single Responsibility

Modules that grow beyond a single orchestrator MUST be decomposed:

1. **Custom hook** for state + side effects → `useFeatureFlow.ts`
2. **Sub-components** for each distinct UI section (banners, forms, views)
3. **Thin orchestrator** that composes hook + sub-components

```
modules/Login/
  useLoginFlow.ts          → State machine, side effects, error handling
  LoginForm.tsx            → Email input + submit
  GoogleSignInButton.tsx   → Google auth button
  AuthBanner.tsx           → Warning/error banners
  LinkSentView.tsx         → Confirmation screen
  VerifyingView.tsx        → Loading screen
  AuthDivider.tsx          → Visual separator
  Login.tsx                → Thin orchestrator (composes above)
  Login.types.ts           → Enums, interfaces, flow state contract
```

## Enums & Constants — No Magic Strings

- Status/state values MUST be TypeScript `enum` (e.g., `LoginStatus.Idle`)
- Route paths MUST be `as const` objects (e.g., `LoginRoutes.CreateAccount`)
- Error codes MUST use existing enums (e.g., `AuthErrorCode.UNKNOWN`)
- NEVER use hardcoded strings for status, routes, or error codes
